Regression Modeling for Rental Property Price Prediction

Mithirendra Maniam

2023-11-15

1. Introduction

Renting a property is expensive in KL and Selangor. The purpose of this project is to build a linear regression model to predict the price of a property based on its size and number of bedrooms.

2. Data Collection

Data was obtained from Kaggle. The URL for the dataset is given here: [Property Rental Data] (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ariewijaya/rent-pricing-kuala-lumpur-malaysi/download?datasetVersionNumber=5)

This dataset contains information on rent pricing surrounding Kuala Lumpur and Selangor region, Malaysia. The information was scraped from mudah.my.

There are 13 features with one unique ids (ads_id) and one target feature (monthly_rent)

  • ads_id: the listing ids (unique)
  • prop_name: name of the building/ property
  • completion_year: completion/ established year of the property
  • monthly_rent: monthly rent in ringgit malaysia (RM)
  • location: property location in Kuala Lumpur region
  • property_type:property type such as apartment, condominium, flat, duplex, studio, etc
  • rooms: number of rooms in the unit
  • parking: number of parking space for the unit
  • bathroom: number of bathrooms in the unit
  • size: total area of the unit in square feet
  • furnished: furnishing status of the unit (fully, partial, non-furnished)
  • facilities: main facilities available
  • additional_facilities: additional facilities (proximity to attraction area, mall, school, shopping, railways, etc)

We are looking for 3 variables to perform the prediction, namely monthly_rent, size and rooms. From the structure of the dataset above, it can be seen that all 3 variables are character classes. We should subset the columns in a new variable and convert this character variables into numeric variables so that we can run a regression model.

Also added the property type column to be able to choose the type of property, to allow for more accurate prediction.

# Subset a few columns to create a new subset dataset

5. Data Modeling and Prediction

Building a linear regression model using size and rooms to predict monthly rent.

# Build a linear regression model
model <- lm(monthly_rent ~ rooms + size, data=subprop_data)
summary(model)

6. Outcome - Predicting Price based on input of size and rooms

# Function for predicting property rental
rental_predictor <- function(type, size, rooms) {
  subprop_type <- subprop_data[subprop_data$property_type == type,  ]
  model <- lm(monthly_rent ~ rooms + size, data=subprop_type)
  newdata <- data.frame(size, rooms)
  prediction <- predict(model, newdata)
  print(paste("The predicted rental price for a", type, "property with", rooms, "rooms and a size of", size,"sq feet is: ~RM", round(prediction,0)))
}
rental_predictor("Apartment",1200, 3)
## [1] "The predicted rental price for a Apartment property with 3 rooms and a size of 1200 sq feet is: ~RM 1406"
rental_predictor("Condominium",1000,3)
## [1] "The predicted rental price for a Condominium property with 3 rooms and a size of 1000 sq feet is: ~RM 1715"
rental_predictor("Studio",400,1)
## [1] "The predicted rental price for a Studio property with 1 rooms and a size of 400 sq feet is: ~RM 1053"
